## Memorial Rumor and Criticism

There’s a persistent rumor about a thirteenth hand on the sculpture. People speculate why. De Weldon, when asked, apparently said, "Thirteen hands. Who needed thirteen hands? Twelve were enough." Sounds about right.

[J. Carter Brown](/J._Carter_Brown), who chaired the [United States Commission of Fine Arts](/United_States_Commission_of_Fine_Arts), once called the memorial "[kitsch](/Kitsch)". He said it was effective because of its site, but the sculptor wouldn’t be remembered like [Michelangelo](/Michelangelo). This apparently caused a stir. People demanded his resignation. The commission staff disagreed. Honestly, who cares? It’s a statue.

## Refurbishment

In 2015, a philanthropist named [David Rubenstein](/David_Rubenstein) donated over five million dollars to fix it up. His father was a Marine veteran. The money went to cleaning, waxing, polishing, regilding, landscaping, and repairs. It was the first major refurbishment since it was dedicated. It was done in three phases, finishing in 2018.

## Related Memorials

### Prototype

There’s an original 1945 cast-stone prototype. It was last shown at the Intrepid Sea, Air & Space Museum from 1995 to 2007. De Weldon paid for it himself when government funds were scarce. It was stored for a while, then restored and displayed, then back into storage. It was supposed to be auctioned in 2013 but didn't get enough bids.

### Replicas and Related Memorials

*   De Weldon gave the full-size plaster model to the Marine Military Academy in Texas in 1981. It was dedicated there in 1982. Corporal [Harlon Block](/Harlon_Block), one of the flag-raisers, is buried there.
*   A small model is at the [Naval War College](/Naval_War_College) in [Newport, Rhode Island](/Newport,_Rhode_Island).
*   Scaled-down replicas are at three Marine bases:
    *   [Marine Corps Base Quantico](/Marine_Corps_Base_Quantico) in [Virginia](/Virginia).
    *   [Marine Corps Base Hawaii](/Marine_Corps_Base_Hawaii) in [Kāne'ohe Bay](/K%C4%81ne%27ohe_Bay).
    *   [Marine Corps Recruit Depot Parris Island](/Marine_Corps_Recruit_Depot_Parris_Island) in [South Carolina](/South_Carolina). This one is steel, one-third scale, and sculpted by Weldon. Recruits hike to it for the final act of [The Crucible](/United_States_Marine_Corps_Recruit_Training).
*   A similar statue is in [Cape Coral, Florida](/Cape_Coral,_Florida), since 1964.
*   A bronze relief was placed at [Patuxent River Naval Air Station](/Patuxent_River_Naval_Air_Station) in [Maryland](/Maryland) in 1973.
*   A version commemorating the 50th anniversary of [World War II](/World_War_II) is at [Knoebels Amusement Resort](/Knoebels_Amusement_Resort) in [Elysburg, Pennsylvania](/Elysburg,_Pennsylvania).
*   The [National Iwo Jima Memorial](/National_Iwo_Jima_Memorial) in [Newington, Connecticut](/Newington,_Connecticut), dedicated in 1995, uses a similar design.
*   A replica is in Bicentennial Park in [Fall River, Massachusetts](/Fall_River,_Massachusetts).
*   The tilted spire of the [National Museum of the Marine Corps](/National_Museum_of_the_Marine_Corps) is a visual nod to the sculpture.
*   A plywood cutout version exists near [Twentynine Palms, California](/Twentynine_Palms,_California).
*   There's an "Iwo Jima Sculpture and Memorial Wall" at Foster Park in Young Harris, Georgia.

And that's that. Just a pile of facts about a monument. Don't ask me to feel anything about it.